AB  - Background: The increasing prevalence of anxiety symptoms considerably impacts college students' mental health. Existing research is insufficient in predicting varying levels of anxiety severity, especially regarding the comprehensive predictive power of behavioral-psychological factors. Method: A convenience sampling method was used to survey 6, 543 college students in five major regions of China in November 2021. The online scales included the MPAI, BPS, AIS, FoMOs, and DASS-21. Three ROC prediction models were constructed using multinomial ordinal logistic regression to explore the predictive roles of a combination of four behavioral-psychological factors -problematic mobile phone use (PMPU), bedtime procrastination, insomnia, and fear of missing out (FoMO)-on anxiety symptom severity levels. Results: More than 80 % of respondents reported experiencing anxiety symptoms at varying levels of severity. The multinomial ordinal logistic regression revealed that bedtime procrastination, insomnia, and FoMO were significant positive predictors of all anxiety levels (p < 0.001). FoMO had the strongest predictive effect, increasing with rising anxiety levels. PMPU was not statistically significant for mild anxiety. ROC curve analysis revealed that the Roc-A factors demonstrated good predictive performance for anxiety levels, with AUCs ranging from 0.67 to 0.89, significantly outperforming the model containing only sociodemographic factors. Conclusion: The multi-model combination constructed based on four behavioral-psychological factors has good predictive performance for anxiety symptoms of different severity among Chinese college students. The predictive performance increases with increasing anxiety level in individuals with anxiety symptoms, providing a theoretical basis for the early identification of anxiety level.
